Fix the root cause of the React duplicate key storm by assigning a stable `_partId` field to each new text part when it is first created in `stream-event-handler.ts`. The `_partId` is a client-only streaming concern — it is never serialized or sent over the wire. The `TextPartSchema` in `packages/shared` must NOT be changed.

## Files to Modify

- `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/stream-event-handler.ts`

## Root Cause

Line 139 creates a new text part without any stable identifier:
```ts
// BEFORE — no _partId, so React key falls back to index i
currentPartsRef.current = [...parts, { type: 'text', text }];
```

When the `parts` array changes shape (e.g., text → tool_call → text), the index-based key `text-${i}` can collide, generating ~300 React "Encountered two children with the same key" warnings per streaming response.

## Type Definition

Define a local type at the top of `stream-event-handler.ts` (after existing imports, before the `StreamEventDeps` interface):

```ts
// Client-only streaming type — _partId is never serialized or sent over the wire.
// It provides a stable React key for text parts during streaming, where the parts
// array is rebuilt on every text_delta event.
type StreamingTextPart = { type: 'text'; text: string; _partId: string };
```

## Fix: Assign _partId at Part Creation (Line 139)

```ts
case 'text_delta': {
  const { text } = data as TextDelta;
  const parts = currentPartsRef.current;
  const lastPart = parts[parts.length - 1];
  if (lastPart && lastPart.type === 'text') {
    // Immutable update — avoid mid-mutation reads under concurrent rendering
    // The spread { ...lastPart, text: ... } preserves _partId automatically.
    currentPartsRef.current = [
      ...parts.slice(0, -1),
      { ...lastPart, text: lastPart.text + text },
    ];
  } else {
    // NEW TEXT PART: assign _partId once at creation.
    // parts.length is the stable position of this part in the array at the moment
    // of creation. This value is deterministic, cheap, and sufficient for key stability.
    const partId = `text-part-${parts.length}`;
    const newPart: StreamingTextPart = { type: 'text', text, _partId: partId };
    currentPartsRef.current = [...parts, newPart];
  }
  // ... rest of case unchanged
}
```

## Key Invariants

1. `_partId` is assigned exactly once per text part — at creation in the `else` branch.
2. Subsequent `text_delta` events that append to the same part (the `if (lastPart.type === 'text')` branch) use `{ ...lastPart, text: ... }` — the spread preserves `_partId` automatically without any additional code.
3. `_partId` is never mutated after assignment.
4. The counter `parts.length` at creation time is the stable position index. It is not globally unique across all parts — it is unique among text parts within a single streaming session, which is sufficient.

## Why Not UUID?

`crypto.randomUUID()` would also work but is unnecessarily complex — the positional counter string `text-part-N` is deterministic, cheap, and sufficient. The key's purpose is stability within a single streaming session, not global uniqueness.

## Why Not Modify TextPartSchema?

`TextPartSchema` is in `packages/shared/src/schemas.ts` and is part of the wire protocol. Changing it would require updating the server transcript parser, the SDK integration layer, and all consumers. The `_partId` is exclusively a client-side streaming concern — it belongs in `stream-event-handler.ts` only.

## TypeScript Compatibility

The `currentPartsRef` is typed as `MessagePart[]`. `StreamingTextPart` is a subtype of `MessagePart`'s text variant (it extends it with `_partId`). The assignment `currentPartsRef.current = [...parts, newPart]` may require a type assertion or the `StreamingTextPart` can be cast as `MessagePart` at the assignment site:

```ts
currentPartsRef.current = [...parts, newPart as MessagePart];
```

Or widen the ref type to include `_partId` optional on text parts:
```ts
// Alternative: no cast needed if the ref is widened
type StreamPart = MessagePart | StreamingTextPart;
```

Use whichever approach TypeScript accepts without errors. The simplest is the `as MessagePart` cast.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Line 139 of `stream-event-handler.ts` assigns `_partId: \`text-part-${parts.length}\`` to new text parts
- [ ] The `if (lastPart.type === 'text')` branch at lines 132-137 is unchanged — spread naturally preserves `_partId`
- [ ] `TextPartSchema` in `packages/shared/src/schemas.ts` is NOT modified
- [ ] TypeScript compiles without errors
- [ ] No new external dependencies introduced

Update the React key used for text parts in `AssistantMessageContent.tsx` to use `_partId` when available (streaming parts) and fall back to the index-based key (history-loaded parts that never go through the streaming handler).

## Files to Modify

- `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/message/AssistantMessageContent.tsx`

## Root Cause (Component Side)

Line 121:
```tsx
// BEFORE — index-based key causes collisions when parts array shape changes
<div key={`text-${i}`} className="msg-assistant">
```

When streaming produces a `parts` array like `[text, tool_call, text]`, React sees two elements with `key="text-0"` and `key="text-2"` — no collision. But when the shape changes mid-stream (e.g., a new tool call pushes the second text part from index 2 to index 1), the keys shift and React reports "Encountered two children with the same key".

## Required Change (Line 121)

```tsx
// AFTER — use _partId when available, fall back to index for history-loaded parts
<div
  key={(part as { _partId?: string })._partId ?? `text-${i}`}
  className="msg-assistant"
>
```

## Why the Fallback is Safe

- **Streaming parts** (through `stream-event-handler.ts`): have `_partId` assigned at creation. The key is stable regardless of array shape changes.
- **History-loaded parts** (from `mapHistoryMessage` in `use-chat-session.ts`): never go through the streaming handler, so they have no `_partId`. These parts are loaded once and the array does not change shape, so index-based keys are safe.

## Full Context of the Text Part Block

The existing code at lines 116-128:
```tsx
return (
  <>
    {parts.map((part, i) => {
      if (part.type === 'text') {
        return (
          <div key={`text-${i}`} className="msg-assistant">
            <StreamingText
              content={part.text}
              isStreaming={isStreaming && i === lastTextPartIndex}
            />
          </div>
        );
      }
      // ... tool call, approval, question branches below
    })}
  </>
);
```

After the fix:
```tsx
return (
  <>
    {parts.map((part, i) => {
      if (part.type === 'text') {
        return (
          <div
            key={(part as { _partId?: string })._partId ?? `text-${i}`}
            className="msg-assistant"
          >
            <StreamingText
              content={part.text}
              isStreaming={isStreaming && i === lastTextPartIndex}
            />
          </div>
        );
      }
      // ... tool call, approval, question branches unchanged
    })}
  </>
);
```

## No Other Changes Needed

The other part types (`tool_call`, `approval`, `question`) already use `part.toolCallId` as their React key (lines 132-166), which is stable. Only the text part key needs updating.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Line 121 of `AssistantMessageContent.tsx` uses `(part as { _partId?: string })._partId ?? \`text-${i}\`` as the key
- [ ] The fallback `\`text-${i}\`` is present for history-loaded parts without `_partId`
- [ ] No other changes to the component logic (tool call, approval, question branches unchanged)
- [ ] TypeScript compiles without errors
- [ ] The type cast `as { _partId?: string }` is used (not type widening of `MessagePart`, since `TextPartSchema` must not change)

